From: Adriel Santos <adriel@adriel.eu>
Subject: [PATCH] nss: an8855: install host FDB/MDB entries in the tag_8021q VID (layered after 999-2757)

Under tag_8021q the data path never classifies frames into VID 0: a
bridged port's PVID is the tag_8021q bridge VID, a standalone port's
PVID is its standalone VID, and the FDB runs independent VLAN learning
(IVL). But .port_fdb_add/.port_fdb_del receive vid 0 for every host
entry installed by assisted learning on the CPU port (the bridge is
VLAN-unaware), and the driver's "default vid" fallback keeps it 0
(AN8855_PORT_VID_DEFAULT is 0).

The result is two disjoint FDB keyspaces: host entries for wifi/CPU-side
MACs live at (mac, 0) -> CPU while hardware learning on the bridged
user ports (re-enabled per BR_LEARNING) populates (mac, bridge VID) ->
LAN port. A client roaming from a peer AP onto local wifi still has its
stale hardware-learned (mac, bridge VID) entry pointing at the backhaul
LAN port; the CPU host entry at (mac, 0) never displaces it. Every
downstream unicast to the client - DHCP OFFER/ACK first of all -
ingresses that same backhaul port, hits the stale entry, and is
same-port filtered. DHCP-after-roam fails until the entry ages out
(~300 s), which the client's retry loop usually re-arms.

Verified live on the failing unit via the an8855_dsa netlink interface:
a (mac, bridge VID) -> CPU entry delivers LAN-ingress unicast through
the vbid RX path to the wifi netdevs, the stale -> ingress-port entry
black-holes it, and an absent entry floods correctly via UNUF.

Fix like sja1105_fdb_add does: translate vid 0 per the dsa_db the entry
belongs to (DSA_DB_BRIDGE -> dsa_tag_8021q_bridge_vid, DSA_DB_PORT ->
dsa_tag_8021q_standalone_vid), and set ds->fdb_isolation so DSA keeps
db.bridge.num intact. The host entry then lands on the same IVL key as
the stale learned entry and overwrites it, steering downstream unicast
to the CPU. Apply the same translation to the MDB ops (same vid-0
fallback; inert with IGMP snooping off, but keeps the keyspace
consistent), and hide the tag_8021q VIDs from 'bridge fdb' dumps like
sja1105 does.

Layered after 999-2757 (add an8855 v2p0p1 + netlink) for the same
reason as 999-2758: that patch rewrites the surrounding hunks on top of
the files overlay. NSS-only; the base MTK-tag build has a single FDB
keyspace and is unaffected.

Link: https://github.com/ADCDS/openwrt-xiaomi-ax3000t-rd03v2/issues/7
--- a/drivers/net/dsa/an8855.c
+++ b/drivers/net/dsa/an8855.c
@@ -546,6 +546,31 @@
 	mutex_unlock(&priv->reg_mutex);
 }
 
+/* tag_8021q: data-path frames never classify into VID 0 - a bridged port's
+ * PVID is the tag_8021q bridge VID and a standalone port's PVID is its
+ * standalone VID, and the FDB runs independent VLAN learning. Host entries
+ * from assisted learning arrive here with vid 0 (VLAN-unaware bridge), so
+ * they must be translated into the VID the lookup actually uses. Otherwise a
+ * client roaming onto local wifi keeps hitting the stale hardware-learned
+ * (mac, bridge VID) entry that still points at the LAN port it used to live
+ * behind - and every downstream frame to it ingresses that same port and is
+ * same-port filtered (issue #7). Same model as sja1105.
+ */
+static u16 an8855_fdb_vid(u16 vid, struct dsa_db db)
+{
+	if (vid)
+		return vid;
+
+	switch (db.type) {
+	case DSA_DB_PORT:
+		return dsa_tag_8021q_standalone_vid(db.dp);
+	case DSA_DB_BRIDGE:
+		return dsa_tag_8021q_bridge_vid(db.bridge.num);
+	default:
+		return 0;
+	}
+}
+
 static int an8855_port_fdb_add(struct dsa_switch *ds, int port,
 			       const unsigned char *addr, u16 vid,
 			       struct dsa_db db)
@@ -554,9 +579,9 @@
 	u8 port_mask = BIT(port);
 	int ret;
 
-	/* With VLAN-Unaware entry, set vid to default vid */
+	vid = an8855_fdb_vid(vid, db);
 	if (!vid)
-		vid = AN8855_PORT_VID_DEFAULT;
+		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 
 	mutex_lock(&priv->reg_mutex);
 	an8855_fdb_write(priv, vid, port_mask, addr, true);
@@ -574,9 +599,9 @@
 	u8 port_mask = BIT(port);
 	int ret;
 
-	/* With VLAN-Unaware entry, set vid to default vid */
+	vid = an8855_fdb_vid(vid, db);
 	if (!vid)
-		vid = AN8855_PORT_VID_DEFAULT;
+		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 
 	mutex_lock(&priv->reg_mutex);
 	an8855_fdb_write(priv, vid, port_mask, addr, false);
@@ -634,7 +659,12 @@
 
 			if (!_fdb.live)
 				continue;
-			ret = cb(_fdb.mac, _fdb.vid, _fdb.noarp, data);
+			/* Hide the tag_8021q VIDs from the user, like
+			 * sja1105 does - they are an implementation detail.
+			 */
+			ret = cb(_fdb.mac,
+				 vid_is_dsa_8021q(_fdb.vid) ? 0 : _fdb.vid,
+				 _fdb.noarp, data);
 			if (ret < 0)
 				break;
 		}
@@ -1007,9 +1037,10 @@
 	u32 val;
 	int ret;
 
-	/* With VLAN-Unaware entry, set vid to default vid */
+	/* Same tag_8021q VID translation as the FDB entries above */
+	vid = an8855_fdb_vid(vid, db);
 	if (!vid)
-		vid = AN8855_PORT_VID_DEFAULT;
+		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 
 	mutex_lock(&priv->reg_mutex);
 
@@ -1044,9 +1075,10 @@
 	u32 val;
 	int ret;
 
-	/* With VLAN-Unaware entry, set vid to default vid */
+	/* Same tag_8021q VID translation as the FDB entries above */
+	vid = an8855_fdb_vid(vid, db);
 	if (!vid)
-		vid = AN8855_PORT_VID_DEFAULT;
+		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 
 	mutex_lock(&priv->reg_mutex);
 
@@ -2236,6 +2268,12 @@
 	 */
 	ds->assisted_learning_on_cpu_port = true;
 
+	/* Keep db.bridge.num intact in fdb_add/del calls - without this DSA
+	 * forces it to 0 and the tag_8021q bridge-VID translation in
+	 * an8855_fdb_vid() would compute the wrong VID. Matches sja1105.
+	 */
+	ds->fdb_isolation = true;
+
 	/* tag_8021q bridging: bridges must get unique nonzero numbers so
 	 * dsa_tag_8021q_bridge_join() derives a distinct bridge VID. DSA only
 	 * hands those out when max_num_bridges is set; otherwise bridge.num
